Throughout the following assumptions are being made:

      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states

  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00797006 Eh      5.00 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01382065 Eh      8.67 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01914289 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04197089 Eh     26.34 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00729500 Eh      4.58 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01383090 Eh      8.68 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01914289 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol

Final entropy term                ...      0.04130607 Eh     25.92 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00728497 Eh      4.57 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01383267 Eh      8.68 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01914289 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol

Final entropy term                ...      0.04129781 Eh     25.91 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00729555 Eh      4.58 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01383110 Eh      8.68 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01914289 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04130682 Eh     25.92 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

                  0          1          2          3          4          5    
      0       0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000
      1       0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000
      2       0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000
      3       0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000   0.000000

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

freq.    3268.38  E(vib)   ...       0.00 

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Translational entropy             ...      0.01914289 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00729523 Eh      4.58 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01383120 Eh      8.68 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01914289 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04130660 Eh     25.92 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00729423 Eh      4.58 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01383106 Eh      8.68 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01914289 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04130546 Eh     25.92 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00729283 Eh      4.58 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01383116 Eh      8.68 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01914289 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04130416 Eh     25.92 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES

M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:
Electronic energy                ...   -384.21940648 Eh
Zero point energy                ...      0.13113460 Eh      82.29 kcal/mol
Thermal vibrational correction   ...      0.00449232 Eh       2.82 kcal/mol
Thermal rotational correction    ...      0.00141627 Eh       0.89 kcal/mol
Thermal translational correction ...      0.00141627 Eh       0.89 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Total thermal energy                   -384.08094703 Eh

(perhaps to be used in another calculation)

Non-thermal (ZPE) correction              0.13113460 Eh      82.29 kcal/mol

--------
ENTHALPY
--------

The enthalpy is H = U + kB*T

Chem.Eur.J. 2012 18 9955


-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00729418 Eh      4.58 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01383104 Eh      8.68 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01914289 Eh     12.01 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04130540 Eh     25.92 kcal/mol
